ron:e7885813 is still actively running with an updatedAt timestamp of 19:05 UTC, and cron:e7885813 (zombie) hasn't changed since the last check, so all four critical sessions remain stable with no state transitions or new failures. Looking at the Telegram group session more carefully—the last activity was at 18:15 UTC, which is about 56 minutes old. That's within acceptable bounds for a monitoring session, so it doesn't constitute a state change requiring a report. I'm checking whether the heartbeat-state.json baseline matches what I'm seeing in the current data, and it does—the Telegram group and cron:e7885813 were both already accounted for in the baseline as running sessions. All sessions are accounted for in the heartbeat state with no changes since the last check, so I'm ready to update the heartbeat-state.json file with the new timestamp and current session statuses. The baseline from 18:26 UTC still matches the current state—those same four cron sessions are running, and while the telegram group updated its timestamp, it was already marked as running in the baseline, so there's no actual change to report.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"text\",\n              \"text\": \"Comparing current state (19:11 UTC) vs. stored baseline (18:26 UTC):\\n\\n| Session | Baseline | Current | Δ |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| cron:ed2d0b5d | ✅ running | ✅ running (updatedAt 19:09 UTC) | — |\\n| cron:6f3323ef | ✅ running | ✅ running (updatedAt 19:11 UTC) | — |\\n| cron:e7885813 | ✅ running | ✅ running (updatedAt 19:05 UTC) | — |\\n| telegram:group:-5163901258 | ✅ running | ✅ running (updatedAt 19:03 UTC) | — |\\n\\n**No state transitions. No new failures. No blockers. Pipeline stable.**\\n\\nSilent exit — no report sent.\"\n            }\n          ],\n          \"api\": \"anthropic-messages\",\n          \"provider\": \"ahvholding\",\n          \"model\": \"AHV-Holding-DEV\",\n          \"usage\": {\n            \"input\": 28868,\n            \"output\":